{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17651498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17651498"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:24:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:24:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18461"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18461"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0,0.29,0.5,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11190"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77718"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11190","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11190"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18461"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63234"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5641"},{"type":"tags","id":"5700"},{"type":"tags","id":"5710"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25955"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25995"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77718","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77718"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman is interested in becoming an organ donor. During a discussion with her general practitioner about organ donation, she asks about the ethical principles that protect potential donors.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the dead donor rule?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Donors must have previously registered their consent","Donors must be brain dead for at least 24 hours","Organ procurement must not cause the death of the donor","Donors must be certified deceased by two independent physicians","Donors must have no cardiac activity for 5 minutes"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eorgan procurement must not cause the death of the donor\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct definition of the dead donor rule. This fundamental ethical principle ensures that the process of organ donation itself cannot be the cause of a donor\u0027s death. The rule exists to protect vulnerable patients and maintain public trust in organ donation programs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDonors must have previously registered their consent\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect; while consent is essential for organ donation, this is a separate legal requirement and not part of the dead donor rule.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDonors must be brain dead for at least 24 hours\u003C/strong\u003E is also incorrect; brain death is one pathway to organ donation, but there is no mandatory waiting period specified in the dead donor rule.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Edonors must be certified deceased by two independent physicians\u003C/strong\u003E is a common practice in many jurisdictions, this is a procedural safeguard rather than the dead donor rule itself.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDonors must have no cardiac activity for 5 minutes\u003C/strong\u003E relates to donation after circulatory death protocols but is not part of the dead donor rule definition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe dead donor rule ensures that vital organs are only procured from patients who are already deceased, whether by neurological or circulatory criteria. This maintains ethical standards and public trust in transplantation medicine.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The dead donor rule states that organ donation must not cause death of the donor.","Vital organs can only be procured from patients who are already deceased.","The dead donor rule protects both donors and the integrity of the transplantation process."],"references":["Mandal J, Ponnambath DK, Parija SC. Bioethics: A brief review. Trop Parasitol. 2017;7(1):5-7. doi:10.4103/tp.TP_4_17","Varkey B. Principles of Clinical Ethics and Their Application to Practice. Med Princ Pract. 2021;30(1):17-28. doi:10.1159/000509119","Truog RD, Robinson WM. Role of brain death and the dead-donor rule in the ethics of organ transplantation. Crit Care Med. 2003;31(9):2391-2396. doi:10.1097/01.CCM.0000090869.19410.3C"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63234"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18461"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63234","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63234"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T07:56:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T22:04:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11190"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77718"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},